kdrop of ancient monasteries,castles and mouldering ruins, and authors such as Robert Burns, James Hogg and Walter Scott drew on the macabre to colour their depictions of Scottish life. Meanwhile, folk culture used apparitions to talk about morality and mortality. Focusing on the period from 1685 to 1830, this book provides the first academic study of the history of Scottish ghosts. Drawing on a wide range of sources, and examining beliefs across the social spectrum, it shows howghost stories achieved a new prominence in a period that is more usually associated with the rise of rationalism. In exploring perceptions of ghosts, it also reflects on understandings of death and the afterlife; the constructionof national identity; and the impact of the Enlightenment. MARTHA MCGILL completed her PhD at the University of Edinburgh.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnlightenmentzScotland. 0aGhostsxHistoryy18th centuryzScotland. 0aGhostszScotlandxHistoryy18th century. 0aHaunted placeszScotlandxHistoryy18th century. 4aEarly Modern History. 4aEighteenth Century Studies. 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aModern History. 7aRELIGION / History.2bisacsh  aAge of Enlightenment.  aScotland.  aaffect.  acultural history.  acultural impact.  ademons.  aemotions.  aempathy.  afolklore.  agothic literature.  ainternational reputation.  amorality.  amortality.  anational identity.  aphysicians.  areligious propagandists.  arestless souls.  aromantic literature.  asupernatural.  awalking corpses.  awitches.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311143106240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787443662?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787443662423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/i